{{about| a wildfire|the burning of residue deposits on the inner surfaces of chimney tiles|Chimney fire}} {{Infobox wildfire | title = Chimney Fire | image = ChimneyFire.jpg | caption = Smoke rises from the Chimney Fire on August 14. | cost = | injuries = | fatalities = | reference = <ref name=cdf>{{cite web|title=Chimney Fire|url=http://www.fire.ca.gov/current_incidents/incidentdetails/Index/1389|website=[[CAL FIRE]]|accessdate=2 September 2016}}</ref> <!-- ONLY FOR INDIVIDUAL FIRES --> | date = {{Start date|2016|08|13}} - {{End date|2016|9|6}} | location = [[Santa Lucia Range]], [[San Luis Obispo County, California|San Luis Obispo County]], [[California]] | coordinates = {{coord|35.70595|-120.98316|display=inline,title}} | pushpin_map = California | pushpin_map_caption = Location in California | area = {{Convert| 46,344 |acre|km2|0}} | buildings = {{ubl|70 destroyed|8 damaged}} | motive = }}
The '''Chimney Fire''' was a [[wildfire]] in the [[Santa Lucia Range]], within [[San Luis Obispo County, California|San Luis Obispo County]], [[California]].<ref name=cdf/> The fire temporarily closed [[Hearst Castle]] to tourists and also forced the closure of [[California State Route 1|Highway 1]] along the scenic [[Big Sur]] coast for a time. By the time the fire was contained on September 6, 2016 it had burned {{Convert| 46,344 |acre|km2|0}} acres of land.<ref name=cdf/>
==Events== The fire was first reported Saturday August 13 shortly after 4:00&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=cdf/> Evacuations were ordered in the area of Running Deer Ranch, located on the south side of [[Lake Nacimiento]].<ref name="Nooz1">{{cite news|last1=Holden|first1=Lindsey|title=Wildfire Chars 1,450 Acres Near Lake Nacimiento in San Luis Obispo County|url=https://www.noozhawk.com/article/wildfire_chars_hundreds_of_acres_near_lake_nacimiento_in_san_luis_obispo_co|accessdate=15 August 2016|agency=[[Noozhawk]]|date=13 August 2016}}</ref>
[[File:Chimney Fire burnout operations.JPG|thumb|left|Chimney Fire burnout operations]] On Sunday afternoon the 14th, officials announced that Highway 1 would be closed for at least 24 hours due to fire activity.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Coury|first1=Nic|title=Highway 1 to close; Chimney Fire erupts in SLO county.|url=http://www.montereycountyweekly.com/blogs/news_blog/highway-to-close-chimney-fire-erupts-in-slo-county/article_569f7682-61bd-11e6-84f6-870f3e9294a3.html|accessdate=15 August 2016|date=13 August 2016}}</ref> Dry south-west winds and temperatures approaching {{convert|100|F|C}} drove the fire.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hovde|first1=Dave|title=Chimney Fire weather is warm and breezy with much of the rest of the area mild|url=http://www.ksby.com/story/32757442/chimney-fire-weather-is-warm-and-breezy-with-much-of-the-rest-of-the-area-mild|accessdate=15 August 2016|agency=[[KSBY]]|date=14 August 2016}}</ref>
By Monday morning the fire had grown to over {{convert|4300|acres|km2}}, including within the [[Los Padres National Forest]].<ref name="Nooz2">{{cite news|last1=Leslie|first1=Kaytlyn|title=Chimney Fire Near Nacimiento Lake Remains 10% Contained|url=https://www.noozhawk.com/article/chimney_fire_near_nacimiento_lake_remains_10_percent_contained|accessdate=15 August 2016|agency=[[Noozhawk]]|date=15 August 2016}}</ref> At a briefing on Monday morning, August 15, officials warned that the area had not burned since the 1960s meaning there is a significant amount of dry, flammable brush that could cause dramatic fire behavior.<ref name="Nooz2"/> Officials from [[CAL FIRE]] also stated that at least 20 homes had been damaged or destroyed, but made clear that the extent of the damage would not be known until crews could enter the burned areas to make a full assessment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chimney Fire containment remains at 10%; 4,300 acres burned|url=http://www.ksby.com/story/32760582/chimney-fire-containment-remains-at-10-4300-acres-burned|accessdate=15 August 2016|agency=[[KSBY]]|date=15 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.montereyherald.com/general-news/20160901/soberanes-fire-could-be-beneficial-for-condors |title=Soberanes Fire could be beneficial for condors |first=Tommy |last=Wright |newspaper=[[Monterey Herald]] |date=September 1, 2016 |access-date=4 September 2016}}</ref>
At {{convert|17,000 |acre|km2}} on Saturday afternoon with 35% containment, the fire was within {{convert|2|miles}} of [[Hearst Castle]]. Tours were cancelled as park staff prepared to move some of the massive art and antiques collection if necessary.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-hearst-castle-threatened-20160820-snap-htmlstory.html |title=Hearst Castle threatened by fast-moving Chimney Fire |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Frank |last=Shyong |date= August 20, 2016 |access-date=21 August 2016}}</ref> No artwork was in any immediate danger, and did not have to be moved.
On August 26, thirteen days after the fire started, the fire neared being half contained, i.e., 49 residences and 21 other structures were destroyed, nearly 1900 other structures were threatened, {{Convert| 45,008 |acre|km2|0}} had been burned, and it was 47% contained.<ref name=cdf/>
As of August 31, the fire had burned {{Convert|46,344| acre|km2}} and was 85% contained. All evacuation orders and road closures have been lifted. The firefighting effort is starting to wind down, although copious smoke is still evident on windy days, and the fire is still uncontrolled towards the northwest. <ref> [http://www.fire.ca.gov/current_incidents/incidentdetails/Index/1389 Cal Fire status report, 8/31/2016] </ref>
